programme.title: Sustainable Futures - Deforestation
programme.desc: Forests across the globe are declining at an incredible rate. Population growth, poverty, and unequal access to land are among the major causes. In Brazil, an Amazon Rain Forestry Project controls illegal logging, improved certification of land ownership, and preservation projects to drive deforestation down. For years, Indonesia has made money by chopping down its forests, but recently some companies have been exercising responsible environmental management.

programme.title: Sustainable Futures - Eco Tourism & Sustainable Development
programme.desc: Ecotourism, responsible tourism and sustainable development have become prevalent concepts since the mid 1980s, and ecotourism has experienced arguably the fastest growth of all sub-sectors in the tourism industry. The popularity represents a change in tourist perceptions, increased environmental awareness, and a desire to explore natural environments. Greener travel, environmentally friendly practices and eco experiences are very much today on the top of modern traveller's wish lists.

programme.title: Sustainable Futures - Economic Issue
programme.desc: For humans, sustainability is the potential for long-term maintenance of wellbeing, which has environmental, economic, and social dimensions. Sustainability economics involves ecological economics where social, cultural, and financial aspects are integrated. In this episode we look at how business and industry are tackling the problem to lower carbon, the increasing value of bio-fuels, innovative methods and practices in India and Chile and the role solar energy is playing in China.

programme.title: Sustainable Futures - Energy Issues
programme.desc: Humankind faces some very difficult choices - our beautiful planet cannot support 6 billion people without fossil fuel. Fossil energy will become rare and expensive in the not very distant future. In China recently, resurgences in nuclear energy have emerged, as the world's most populous country consumes more and more energy. A United Kingdom family tests their energy consumption and shows us all how that by making small changes we can have an impact.

programme.title: Sustainable Futures - Food Production
programme.desc: As climate change continues to progress, the plight of poverty and hunger increase. Farmers are facing new challenges in trying to adapt to the ever changing conditions of their ecosystem. As the demands for food production increases, producers struggle to find ways to balance the needs of the people with economically and environmentally sustainable solutions.

programme.title: Sustainable Futures - Global Warming
programme.desc: In the past few years, the world has experienced many devastating natural disasters. There is much speculation that these phenomena are due to global climate changes and Global Warming. In Western Greenland, scientists say that they have found evidence that the island's massive glaciers are melting. In the USA, the Rocky Mountain labs offer a rare long-term view of the environment and the mountain's local ecosystem.

programme.title: Sustainable Futures - Greenhouse Gases
programme.desc: Greenhouse gases are necessary to life as we know it, because they keep the planet's surface warmer than it otherwise would be. In Greenland, climate researchers are concerned that global warming may ultimately spell an end to Greenland's glaciers, with devastating consequences. In London, scientists are using the radar technology CryoSat to provide reliable 3-D models of the polar ice caps. In the Netherlands, a second generation of resources for bio fuels are being developed.

programme.title: Sustainable Futures - Landfill and Waste Issues
programme.desc: Virtually everything we use creates varying degrees of waste throughout its lifecycle. Today, many nations face a looming waste management crisis, as their landfills reach capacity and continue to degrade the environment. Cheap labor costs in India are propelling a boom in the recycling of computer waste but at the cost of workers' health. Whilst in Manila, achieving 'zero waste' is becoming a reality, as recyclable waste is turned into construction products.

programme.title: Sustainable Futures - Pollution
programme.desc: As the world begins to wake up to the dangers and the damage caused by pollution, the pressure to become more environmentally responsible increases. In India, environmentalists are calling for action to stop the Taj Mahal from turning yellow from the effects of pollution. A New York University study has indicated that living in a city with high levels of air pollution can be as hazardous to your health as living with a smoker and inhaling second hand smoke.

programme.title: Sustainable Futures - Sustainable Living
programme.desc: Living in harmony with the earth is essential to the continued survival of life as we know it. Personal lifestyle changes may seem like a small thing, but collectively it may be the most important component to ensuring a sustainable future. New developments in technology are occurring to help people make these subtle changes easily. Come with us as we explore these changes, all over the world in fields such as environmentally friendly housing, energy efficiency...

programme.title: Sustainable Futures - The Carbon Issue
programme.desc: The ever-growing population and continued economic growth that are taking place worldwide continue to add to the problem of carbon emissions. Activities, which produce carbon emissions fall into four main categories. Electricity generation, transportation, industrial activities and commercial and residential use. Globally, we need to achieve a 90 percent reduction in our carbon emissions by the year 2050 to have a chance at preventing the dangerous effects.
